>[post omitted].

>It is good to have this clarification. However, it does not address the
>appropriateness of the name "USACM" in a headline, which was misunderstood
>by me and several others to mean the U.S. ACM organization, not some
>special-purpose subcommittee speaking only for itself (since ACM does not
>take political positions).

>What is more the press release seems to suggest a monolithic anti-Clipper
>position. I am advised that at least two members of the ACM committee on
>Clipper not only don't hold that view but hold an opposite one. Thus the
>press release misleads in that respect as well. Dorothy Denning is one
>member of the ACM committee that examined Clipper, I am advised. Thus the
>press release seems to me to be more like a distorted propaganda exercise by
>the anti-Clipper forces than a fair representation.

>It is both good and highly praiseworthy that ACM takes itself so seriously
>that its President responded to this issue. It would be good if he seized
>himself of the above points as well.

>David

>-- 
>The values that define our common-sense world are under assault. Some have
>taken to extremes the spurious notion of freedom without responsibility, and
>are trying to tear down moral guardrails. Those who live on the shoulders
>are told by their pals that they are in the middle of the road. Nothing is
>wrong any more (except, of course, conservative thoughts and expressions).

	Is coherent and logical thought a responsibility of freedom, David?

